<!-- 02 TYPICAL FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Common scenarios</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Top commercial grill repairs in our 5-county territory.</h2>

    <p>In rough order of frequency:</p>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Igniter failure (per burner, year 4 to 7 typical).</strong> Gas grill ignition wear from continuous high-heat cycles. Vulcan VCCB uses spark-electrode electrical ignition with replaceable modules; older Garland MGM units use pilot-based ignition where the thermocouple and pilot are paired components. Replacement runs $260 to $440 per burner. We carry common Vulcan and Garland igniter modules on the van.</li>
      <li><strong>Thermocouple wear (year 5 to 8).</strong> Gas safety device, shuts off gas if pilot fails. The thermocouple sees direct flame impingement every cycle and degrades from oxidation. Pair replacement with the igniter on older units to avoid a second visit. $220 to $340.</li>
      <li><strong>Burner head clog (cleaning service).</strong> Grease and carbon buildup affecting flame distribution. Symptom: yellow flame instead of blue, uneven heat across the grill surface, or flame lifting off the burner. Resolves with proper deep cleaning rather than parts replacement. $180 to $290 per burner.</li>
      <li><strong>Radiant element failure (Vulcan VCCB radiant gas grills).</strong> Radiants over burners deteriorate over time, particularly on year 5+ units in busy steakhouse and burger-restaurant settings. Symptom: hot and cold spots across the grill surface, individual radiant glowing dimmer than its neighbors. Replace $290 to $540 per radiant.</li>
      <li><strong>Drip tray drain blockage.</strong> Grease channel clogs, requires deep cleaning plus drain clearing. Common after 6 to 12 months without scheduled cleaning. $200 to $340.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas valve degradation (year 8+).</strong> Main gas control valve, full replacement $580 to $980. Symptom: inconsistent burner output across the unit, slow ignition, or gas-pressure-related complaints from the kitchen.</li>
      <li><strong>Grill grate or plate replacement.</strong> Heavy use deformation. Cast iron grates $290 to $540 each, chrome-plated steel grates $440 to $720 each. Cast iron lasts longer with proper seasoning; chrome plating is easier to clean but warps under year-round high-heat service.</li>
      <li><strong>Lava rock or ceramic briquette replacement.</strong> Older charbroiler-style grills, replacement $80 to $180 per refill. Lava rock breaks down faster (12 to 18 months); ceramic briquettes last longer (24 to 36 months) but cost more upfront.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02b — FIELD OBSERVATIONS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Field observations</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Three things we see on commercial grill calls that aren't in the manual.</h2>

    <p><strong>1. LA commercial grill installs are often gas-line-undersized.</strong> Commercial grills require a 1-inch gas supply line minimum to deliver the 30,000 to 50,000 BTU per burner the equipment is rated for. Older LA restaurant buildouts in West Hollywood, Hollywood, and Koreatown frequently have 1/2-inch residential-spec lines feeding commercial grills, especially when a restaurant moved into a converted retail or residential space. Symptom: grill rated for 4 burners simultaneous use can only run 2 at full output. The fix is gas-line upsizing (specialty plumber trade) before any further service makes sense. We diagnose pressure on every commercial grill call and flag undersized lines so the operator knows the root cause.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Vulcan VCCB radiants degrade unevenly.</strong> The Vulcan VCCB radiant gas char-broiler is the most common LA commercial grill, and its radiant elements (the wire-mesh ceramic plates over each burner) are the consistent year-5-to-8 service item. They don't all fail at once. One radiant deteriorates first, creating a hot-and-cold pattern across the grill that makes consistent cooking impossible. Operators often think the whole grill is failing when it's one radiant element at $290 to $540. We diagnose all radiants, replace the failed ones, and calibrate burner output across the grill.</p>

    <p><strong>3. MagiKitch'n is not residential Wolf.</strong> Same parent corporation (Sub-Zero Group / Wolf Industrial), but completely separate product lines. MagiKitch'n is the commercial restaurant equipment line: heavy-gauge construction, hospital and university dining, premium institutional. Residential Wolf (the Wolf Outdoor or Wolf Range / Wolf Cooktop you might see in a Beverly Hills home) is the home cooking line. Different parts catalogs, different service procedures, different authorized service network. We service both sides because we hold credentials for both residential and commercial scopes, but the service approach is fundamentally different.</p>
  </div>
</section>

